{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Tasaka Tomotaka | image = Tomotaka Tasaka.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1902|4|14}} | birth_place = [[Hiroshima Prefecture]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1974|10|17|1902|4|14}} | death_place = | nationality = Japanese | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Film director }}
{{nihongo|'''Tomotaka Tasaka'''|田坂 具隆|Tasaka Tomotaka|14 April 1902&nbsp;–&nbsp;17 October 1974}} was a [[Japan]]ese [[film director]].
==Career== Born in [[Hiroshima Prefecture]], he began working at [[Nikkatsu]]'s [[Kyoto]] studio in 1924 and eventually came to prominence for a series of realist, humanist films made at Nikkatsu's [[Tama River|Tamagawa]] studio in the late 1930s such as ''[[Robō no ishi]]'' and ''[[Mud and Soldiers]]'', both of which starred [[Isamu Kosugi]].<ref name="kotobank">{{cite web|url=http://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%94%B0%E5%9D%82%E5%85%B7%E9%9A%86|title=Tasaka Tomotaka|work=Nihon jinmei daijiten + Plus|publisher=Kōdansha|language=Japanese|accessdate=11 December 2010}}</ref> His war film, ''[[Five Scouts]]'', was screened in the competition at the [[6th Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000681/1938|title=Venice Film Festival (1938)|work=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=11 December 2010}}</ref>
Tasaka was a victim of the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|atomic bombing of Hiroshima]] and spent many years recovering.<ref name="kotobank" /> He eventually resumed directing and won the best director prize at the 1958 [[Blue Ribbon Awards]] for ''[[A Slope in the Sun]]'', which starred [[Yūjirō Ishihara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinemahochi.yomiuri.co.jp/b_award/1958/|title=Burū Ribon shō historī 1958|publisher=Cinema Hochi|language=Japanese|accessdate=11 December 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120529112603/http://cinemahochi.yomiuri.co.jp/b_award/1958/|archivedate=29 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
His brother, [[Katsuhiko Tasaka]], was also a film director, and his wife, [[Hisako Takihana]], was an actress.
==Selected filmography== * ''[[Five Scouts]]'' (五人の斥候兵, Gonin no sekkōhei) (1938) * ''[[Robō no ishi]]'' (路傍の石) (1938) * ''[[Mud and Soldiers]]'' (土と兵隊, Tsuchi to heitai) (1939) * ''[[The Baby Carriage]]'' (乳母車, Ubaguruma) (1956) * ''[[This Day's Life]]'' (今日のいのち Kyō no inochi) (1957) * ''[[A Slope in the Sun]]'' (陽のあたる坂道, Hi no ataru sakamichi) (1958) * ''[[Lake of Tears (film)|Lake of Tears]]'' (湖の琴, Mizuumi no Kin) (1966)
